A("# The Awakening Census Under the Provenance Signature: A Canonical Corpus That Is Late and Narrated, Not Early Buddha-Word\n")

A("## Abstract\n")
A("An earlier pass enumerated every awakening event in the live corpus and reported two headline facts: awakening is overwhelmingly an occasioned event rather than the climax of solitary striving, and the narrated awakenings live mostly in the commentaries, not the canon. Of 2,214 events, 299 sit in the canon (mula) and 1,915 in the commentarial and extra-canonical layers. That reading is true on its single axis, the structural canon-versus-commentary split, and it conceals a sharper fact that the structural axis cannot see, because the mula tag is a position in the edited corpus and not a date. Recoded under the provenance-signature method, which separates structural layer from chronological stratum and from attribution, the canonical share stops being an early Buddha-word floor. Of the 299 structurally-mula awakening events only 38 are early-canonical (Nikaya prose and Udana); the other 261 carry the mula tag while coding late-canonical, paracanonical, or commentary-era on the chronological axis. The single largest canonical class is the Apadana (162 events, `tha-ap25`, `cst-s0510m1.mul-kn10_1`) [late-canon], a recognised late-canonical autobiographical-verse stratum; the Buddhavamsa (8, `bv10`) [late-canon] and the Niddesa (3, `cnd5`) [late-canon] are late-canonical too; the Visuddhimagga (17, `cst-e0102n.mul-4_p042`) [comm] is structurally tagged mula yet is classical commentary; the Milindapanha (4, `mil3.7.3`) [late-canon] is paracanonical. On attribution the result is starker still. None of the 299 canonical awakening events is the Buddha asserting an awakening in his own mouth. They are redactor-narrated sutta-frame attainments, hagiographic first-person verse (the Apadana speaker recounting his own awakening), or the elder's own Theragatha report with a redactor's colophon. Of the 299, 206 carry first-person self-narration markers and only 22 carry the Buddha-speech frame `bhagava etadavoca` [canon, SQL-confirmed]. The corrected headline is that the canonical awakening corpus is, in the main, a late-canonical and hagiographically-narrated stratum, so the original canon-versus-commentary finding is not overturned but deepened: the contrast it drew is, in part, an early-to-late gradient inside the canon, and at no point is the awakening-event a thing the canon stakes as the Buddha's directly-asserted word.\n")

A("## The corrected headline\n")
A("The most important correction this study makes is not a count but a coordinate change. The earlier reading scored each event on a single structural axis, mula versus the commentarial layers, and concluded that the canon states the Dhamma while the commentaries supply the biography. That axis is preserved here as one row of a fuller signature. What it could not see is that the canon's own share is itself stratified, and that the awakening-event genre is concentrated in the canon's late registers, not its early ones.\n")
A("The corrected headline is this. The genuinely early-canonical awakening events are a small floor of 38 rows: the Nikaya prose suttas where a listener's eye of Dhamma opens at the conclusion of a graduated talk (`dn5`, `mn74`) [canon], and the Udana frame-narratives (`ud1.10`, Bahiya) [canon]. Above that floor sit 261 mula rows that the structural tag calls canonical and the chronological axis re-codes as late. The largest single class, by a wide margin, is the Apadana, the autobiographical past-merit-to-present-awakening verse of named elders, 162 of the 299 canonical events [late-canon]. The Buddhavamsa's mass-awakenings at the feet of past Buddhas are late-canonical lineage verse (`bv10`) [late-canon]. The Niddesa's awakenings sit in a canonical exegesis of the Sutta-nipata, itself late (`cnd5`) [late-canon]. The Visuddhimagga rows are structurally mula in this corpus and are in fact Buddhaghosa's fifth-century scholastic prose (`cst-e0102n.mul-4_p042`) [comm]. The Milindapanha is outside the Tipitaka proper (`mil3.7.3`) [late-canon]. The early Buddha-word floor is real, but it is thin, and the bulk of what the structural axis filed under canon is a late and a narrated corpus.\n")
A("Three things follow that the single axis could not produce. First, the canon-versus-commentary contrast the earlier reading drew is, in part, a chronology gradient running through the canon: the awakening-event genre thins toward the early registers and thickens toward the late and the commentarial ones. Second, the canonical awakening corpus has no Buddha-vacana attribution at all: every one of the 299 events is narrated about an awakening, by a redactor or by the awakened elder, and none is the Buddha staking the attainment as his own asserted claim. Third, the original finding stands and is strengthened: not only do the awakenings live mostly in the commentaries, but even the canon's share is mostly late and hagiographic, so the early-Buddha-word reading the structural tag invites is an overcount.\n")

A("## Methodology\n")
A("### The provenance signature and the triage\n")
A("The method replaces the single canon-versus-commentary axis with a provenance signature, a small triaged set of independent dimensions. The full framework carries eleven axes; the triage maps a research question's load-bearing claims to the axes they actually depend on, and coding every axis on every instance would bury the study.\n")
A("This census is a category-typology question: it enumerates awakening events, whose members are asserted occurrences with a who, a when, and a voice. For a category typology the framework makes the recall ladder, chronological stratum, and attribution load-bearing. The three coded axes are therefore the structural layer (retained as the default-core signal, demoted to one row of the signature), the chronological stratum (coded independently of that layer), and the attribution or speaker of the attainment-claim. The recall ladder is run on the attainment markers as the always-on recall discipline.\n")
A("The axes deliberately not coded, and why, are these. Epistemic marking is excluded because the census records whether an awakening is narrated, not whether it is staked under the canon's verification formula; the load here is on when and by whose voice, which stratum and attribution carry, and an awakening narrated as an event is not the kind of claim the divine-eye formula ranges over. Cross-recensional reach is coded only at link level as a secondary corroboration of the early floor, because the corpus is Pali-only and the Apadana's lateness is settled philologically rather than by a parallel table. Pre-Buddhist provenance is moot, since an awakening event is a Buddhist datum by definition. Harmonization is excluded because no doctrinal tension is being reconciled; the census is descriptive. Reception and edition fire automatically and are reported inside the recall ladder, where the niggahita-glyph cliff is an edition-and-segmentation fact.\n")
A("### The recall ladder\n")
A("Every count rests on a measured enumeration, not an assumed one, and the ladder on the attainment markers is itself a finding. The naive surface string a non-specialist would type for the commonest marker, `arah` plus the bar-niggahita glyph (`arahattaṁ pāpuṇi`), returns 2 rows in the whole corpus (rung 1). The reason is an edition fact: the Chattha Sangayana base writes the niggahita as the dotted-m glyph (`ṃ`), so the bar-m surface string finds almost nothing. Normalising the glyph and admitting the declined and sandhi forms of the arahatta-attainment family (the dotted-m, with `pāpuṇi / patto / pattā / āpādi`) lifts the same family to 914 rows (rung 2). A concept-independent union that searches the awakening-event frame without the word arahatta (the mass-awakening formula `desanāpariyosāne`, the verse-conclusion `gāthāpariyosāne`, the liberation-without-clinging `anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimucci`, the stream-entry `virajaṃ vītamalaṃ dhammacakkhuṃ udapādi`, the destroyed-birth `khīṇā jāti`, the declared-final-knowledge `aññaṃ byākāsi`) reaches 1,488 marker-bearing rows (rung 3). Removing the doctrinal and abstract uses of those markers, the ones that do not narrate an event, leaves the census's net 2,214 events (rung 4).\n")
A("| Rung | Strategy | Yield | Delta | Residual-risk note |")
A("|---|---|---|---|---|")
A("| 1 | naive surface string `arahattaṁ pāpuṇi` (bar-niggahita, as typed), ILIKE | 2 | (base) | the corpus writes the niggahita as the dotted-m glyph, so the bar-m string is near-blind |")
A("| 2 | glyph-normalised (dotted-m) + declension/sandhi of the arahatta-attainment family, regex | 914 | +912 | the glyph normalisation is the dominant recovery |")
A("| 3 | concept/periphrasis union, name-independent (the mass-awakening and path-and-fruit formulae) | 1,488 | +574 | `desanāpariyosāne` is 0 in mula and 206 in attha, a commentarial narrative marker |")
A("| 4 | false-positive purge (doctrinal/abstract marker uses set aside as non-events) | 2,214 | (net) | the census reports 4,023 classified marker rows, 2,214 events and 1,809 non-events |\n")
A("The ladder did not move the census. The earlier pass was already built at the dotted-m depth, so its 299 mula events and its evidence strings carry the dotted-m forms; the rung-1 cliff is a Methods finding about the surface string, not a recall correction to the census. Every load-bearing count below is reconfirmed by a `GROUP BY work_role`, not by the search lane, which over- and under-matches. The regression check is exact: the `GROUP BY work_role` returns mula 299, attha 1,762, tika 118, anya 35, matching the census layer counts to the row.\n")
A("### The work-to-stratum map\n")
A("Chronological stratum is coded from work plus position, never from the structural layer, which is the conflation the axis breaks. Each mula event resolves to exactly one work by a rule over its corpus id and `work_slug`, captured serially from the database. The map follows the consensus relative stratigraphy of Pali philology. AN, SN, MN, DN sutta prose and the Udana are early-canonical. The Apadana, the Buddhavamsa, the Maha- and Cula-niddesa, the Vimanavatthu, and the Vinaya frame-narratives (nidana) are late-canonical. The Milindapanha is paracanonical. The Visuddhimagga, structurally tagged mula in this corpus, is classical commentary on stratum, and is flagged where layer and stratum disagree.\n")
A("Two stratum assignments are coded contested-confidence rather than secure, because they convert a register or position label into a date. The Theragatha and Therigatha (59 events) carry archaic verse, yet the awakening-narration in these rows sits in the redactor-compiled biographical frame attached to the verse, so they are coded `archaic-or-late-canonical` and treated as register-relative rather than securely dated. The Vinaya frame-narratives (6 events) are coded late by their nidana position, a position label and not a secured date. These two are flagged so that no genre or position cue is silently doing duty as a chronology.\n")
A("### Coding and reliability\n")
A("Stratum and attribution are deterministic functions of the work, so the coding is reproducible from the resolved id-to-work manifest without a live database, and the builder recomputes every count from the data. The attribution of each work-class was confirmed by reading representative original rows and by a quotative-marker scan over all 299 mula rows: 206 carry first-person self-narration markers, 22 carry `bhagavā etadavoca`, and 48 carry the redactor's `evaṃ me sutaṃ` or `tena samayena` frame [canon, SQL-confirmed]. Where the corpus carries no English, the rendering is the present author's gloss checked against the standard translations, with load-bearing terms quoted in Pali. The base edition is the Chattha Sangayana (CST/VRI) as ingested; counts and the glyph cliff are relative to that segmentation.\n")

