A("> *Per-claim signature (the canonical floor): [stratum: early-canonical | layer: mula | speaker: redactor-frame | register: prose-doctrinal sutta-frame | recension: several early rows carry external Agama parallels | edition: cst-burmese]. Warrant: `dn5`, `mn74`, `ud1.10`.* [canon]\n")
A("> *Per-claim signature (the late-canonical bulk): [stratum: late-canonical | layer: mula | speaker: hagiographic-self-narration (Apadana) / redactor-frame-verse (Buddhavamsa) | register: narrative-hagiographic verse | recension: Pali, link-level external parallels at work level only | edition: cst-burmese]. Warrant: `tha-ap25`, `cst-s0510m1.mul-kn10_1`, `bv10`.* [late-canon]\n")
A("### The within-canon chronological gradient\n")
A("The awakening-event genre is not spread evenly across the canon's strata; it pools in the late ones. The early-canonical floor is the Nikaya prose where a teaching occasions a listener's stream-entry or arahantship, and the terse Udana. That floor is genuine and it is small. The late-canonical bulk is the autobiographical and lineage verse. The Apadana alone, 162 events, is larger than the entire early floor several times over, and it is a stratum the field places late: the past-life-merit-to-present-awakening biography is exactly the kind of hagiographic elaboration that gathers around the bare canonical fact of an awakening. The Buddhavamsa's serial mass-awakenings at past Buddhas' feet are the same impulse one register out. The Visuddhimagga rows, tagged mula by the corpus's structural column, are fifth-century commentary by any chronology.\n")
A("One honesty guard bounds this. The gradient is relative stratigraphy on consensus philological grounds (Apadana, Buddhavamsa, and Niddesa membership as the late-canonical warrants; Visuddhimagga authorship as the commentary warrant), and it imports no absolute dates. Two assignments are coded contested-confidence because a register or position label is being read as a date: the Theragatha and Therigatha awakening-narration, late by its biographical-frame register rather than by the age of its verse, and the Vinaya alms-flight awakenings, late by their nidana position. Where these are read as merely register-relative, the early floor would grow at most by the Theragatha and Therigatha share; even then the Apadana alone keeps the late bulk decisively larger than the early floor, so the gradient is robust to the contested cells.\n")
A("The cross-recensional check corroborates the early floor at link level. Several of the 33 early-canonical Nikaya-prose awakening events carry external (non-Pali) parallels in the corpus parallel table (Chinese and Sanskrit), a link-level proxy for a pre-sectarian core of the bare awakening narration; the Apadana and Buddhavamsa carry some external parallels at work level too, but the genre's lateness is a philological fact, not a parallel-table absence, and the container-versus-feature distinction is kept: a work-level parallel does not make the autobiographical-verse feature early. This axis is reported as corroboration, not as a load-bearing finding.\n")

A("## The attribution axis: a corpus narrated about the awakened, never staked by the Buddha\n")
A("The sharper of the two retrofit findings is on attribution, the illocutionary owner of the attainment-claim. The structural layer encodes none of this, and the binary buddha-voice tag launders every canonical row into the Buddha's voice. Coded per event-class, the canonical awakening corpus has no Buddha-vacana attribution at all.\n")
A("The honest default the framework sets is that a flat narrated awakening with no quotative owner is a redactor-frame claim, not buddha-vacana; and an explicit quotative warrant is required before coding buddha-vacana. The 299 canonical awakening events fall into four narrating voices, and none of them is the Buddha asserting the awakening.\n")
A('**Hagiographic self-narration (162, the largest).** The Apadana awakenings are first-person verse in which the named elder recounts his own path from a past good deed to his present arahantship. The Tisaranagamaniya elder begins "In the city of Candavati I was a supporter of my mother... I attained" (`tha-ap25`: *Nagare candavatiya, matuupatthako ahum... arahattamapapunim*) [late-canon]. The owner of the attainment-claim is the awakened elder, and the genre is the redactor\'s hagiographic compilation; it is not the Buddha staking the event.\n')
A('**Redactor-frame verse (10).** The Buddhavamsa narrates the mass awakenings at the feet of past Buddhas in lineage verse, the redactor reciting "three abhisamayas occurred... he awakened a hundred koti" (`bv10`) [late-canon]. The Vimanavatthu\'s verse awakenings are the same redactor-narration.\n')
A('**Named-disciple self-report (59).** The Theragatha and Therigatha awakenings are the elder\'s own verse, "having heard his Dhamma I dwelt nearby, mindful; the three knowledges are attained" (`thag1.66`) [canon, contested-stratum], closed by the redactor\'s colophon naming the elder. The owner is the disciple reporting his own attainment, framed by the redactor.\n')
A("**Redactor-frame (64).** The Nikaya-prose, Udana, Niddesa, Vinaya-nidana, and Visuddhimagga awakenings are flat narrated events: the redactor of the sutta or the commentary tells us a listener's mind was freed, with no first-person claim and no Buddha-speech frame asserting the attainment (`ud1.10`, `cst-e0102n.mul-4_p042`) [canon, comm]. The Milindapanha's 4 are Nagasena's dialogue (named-disciple-dialogue), paracanonical.\n")
A("The quotative scan makes the boundary measurable. Of the 299 mula rows, 206 carry first-person self-narration markers (the Apadana and Theragatha \"I attained\"), only 22 carry the Buddha-speech frame `bhagavā etadavoca`, and 48 carry the redactor's `evaṃ me sutaṃ` or `tena samayena` nidana frame [canon, SQL-confirmed]. Even the 22 rows that carry a Buddha-speech frame carry it for the teaching that occasions the awakening, not for an assertion of the awakening itself: the Buddha is the teacher in the scene, not the owner of the attainment-claim. Coded result for the Buddha asserting an awakening in his own mouth: zero of 299.\n")
A("| Attribution | Events | Representative warrant |")
A("|---|---|---|")
A("| `buddha-vacana` (the Buddha asserts the awakening) | 0 | none |")
A("| `hagiographic-self-narration` (Apadana first-person) | 162 | `tha-ap25`, `cst-s0510m1.mul-kn10_1` |")
A("| `redactor-frame` (flat narrated, sutta/commentary frame) | 64 | `ud1.10`, `cst-e0102n.mul-4_p042` |")
A("| `named-disciple-self-report` (Theragatha/Therigatha) | 59 | `thag1.66` |")
A("| `redactor-frame-verse` (Buddhavamsa/Vimanavatthu) | 10 | `bv10` |")
A("| `named-disciple-dialogue` (Milindapanha) | 4 | `mil3.7.3` |\n")
A("The single number that carries the section is the top row: zero [canon, SQL-confirmed]. The bound, stated honestly, is that the canonical awakening corpus is narrated about the awakened rather than asserted by the Buddha; it does not license the stronger and false claim that the Buddha denied or doubted any of these awakenings. The redactor narrates them as fact; the Buddha simply is not the grammatical owner of the claim.\n")
A('> *Per-claim signature (the keystone): Claim "the canon presents an awakening as the Buddha\'s own asserted word". Status: rejected by the attribution scan. [stratum: 38 early-canonical, 261 late-or-later | layer: mula | speaker: 0 buddha-vacana, 206 first-person self-report, 64 redactor-frame, the rest verse-frame or dialogue | register: narrative-hagiographic in the bulk, prose-doctrinal in the early floor | edition: cst-burmese, the glyph cliff edition-relative, the attribution boundary edition-neutral].* [canon, SQL-confirmed]\n')

A("## Discussion\n")
A("The corrected headline is sharper than its predecessor, and the sharpening comes from refusing to let the structural layer stand for the whole provenance question. On the structural axis alone, the awakening census reads as a canon that states the Dhamma and a commentary that supplies the biography, with 299 of 2,214 events in the canon. That sentence is true, and it conceals two facts that change its meaning.\n")
A("First, the canon's own 299 are not an early Buddha-word floor. Only 38 are early-canonical; 261 carry the mula tag while coding late-canonical, paracanonical, or commentary-era, and the largest single class, the Apadana, is late. The canon-versus-commentary contrast the earlier reading drew is therefore, in part, a chronology gradient running through the canon: the awakening-event genre pools in the late and the narrative registers, the autobiographical and the lineage verse, and thins in the early doctrinal prose. The materialisation the structural axis credited to the commentary already begins inside the late canon, in the Apadana and the Buddhavamsa, before any commentary speaks. The qualification is that two of the contested cells (the Theragatha and Therigatha register, the Vinaya nidana position) are register-relative rather than securely dated, and they are coded as such; the gradient survives their removal because the Apadana alone keeps the late bulk decisively larger than the early floor.\n")
A("Second, the deepening runs on a different axis from authorship, and on that axis the canonical awakening corpus has no Buddha-vacana at all. The awakening is a thing the canon narrates about the awakened, in the redactor's frame or in the elder's own hagiographic verse, never a thing the Buddha asserts as his own claim. This is invisible to the binary buddha-voice tag, which counts every canonical row as the Buddha's voice; coded per claim against the quotative markers, the Buddha-asserting count is zero. The finding is not that these awakenings are doubtful, only that their grammatical owner is the redactor or the disciple, and that an early-Buddha-word reading of the canonical share is an overcount on both the chronological and the attribution axes.\n")
A("The methodological lesson matches the one the Uttarakuru retrofit drew on different material. Canon versus commentary is one projection of a richer object, and for any question whose load rests on when a formulation entered (chronological stratum) or in whose mouth a claim is placed (attribution), the single projection misleads in a predictable direction. It will read a late and narrated canonical stratum as an early authored one. The awakening census is a clean case: the structural tag says canon, and the signature says late and narrated.\n")

A("## Limitations\n")
A("The study carries five honest limitations, each stated rather than smoothed.\n")
A("The chronological stratigraphy is relative, not absolute. It rests on consensus Pali philological grounds (Apadana, Buddhavamsa, and Niddesa membership as the late-canonical warrants, Visuddhimagga authorship as the commentary warrant) and imports no absolute dates. Two assignments are coded contested-confidence because a register or position label is being read as a date: the Theragatha and Therigatha awakening-narration, late by its biographical-frame register rather than by the age of its verse, and the Vinaya alms-flight awakenings, late by their nidana position. The early floor would grow at most by the Theragatha and Therigatha share if those cells were read as early; even then the Apadana keeps the late bulk decisively larger, so the gradient is robust to the contested cells.\n")
A("The census is marker-bounded, and the recall ladder measures rather than eliminates that bound. An awakening narrated with no stock attainment phrase is not captured. The ladder reports the floor (the rung-1 glyph cliff, the rung-3 concept union) and the residual risk between the last rung and true totality is visible rather than assumed; the count is claimed as saturated and measured, not as proven-complete.\n")
A("The attribution coding is per work-class, not per individual row. It assigns each work its dominant narrating voice (Apadana self-narration, Buddhavamsa redactor-verse, and so on) and confirms the assignment by the corpus-wide quotative scan, but a small number of individual rows within a class may carry a different local voice; the class-level code is the honest summary, and the zero Buddha-vacana count is robust because no class puts the awakening in the Buddha's asserting mouth.\n")
A("The cross-recensional check is link-level, not feature-level. The corpus bridges out through a parallel table, and the external parallels for the early-canonical floor are evidence about the link table, a proxy for a pre-sectarian core, not an affirmative feature-level reading of the Agama awakening-narrations. This axis is reported as corroboration of the early floor, never as a load-bearing finding.\n")
A("The base edition and the glyph cliff are edition-relative. The recall ladder's rung-1 figure is a fact about the Chattha Sangayana segmentation and its dotted-m niggahita glyph; under a different edition or input convention the surface-string yield would change. What does not change is the structural fact the cliff stands for, that the attainment markers are densely attested once the glyph is normalised, and that the attribution boundary (zero Buddha-vacana) is edition-neutral.\n")

